    About the Business

    Clyde's Tower Oaks Lodge, located just beyond the beltway in suburban Maryland, offers a rustic retreat reminiscent of the grand "Great Camps" of the Adirondack Mountains from the early 1900s. With its grand fireplaces, cozy nooks, and wood-beamed ceilings, Tower Oaks Lodge provides a unique dining experience that combines the rugged beauty of the wilderness with Clyde's Restaurant Group's commitment to exceptional dining and hospitality. Tower Oaks Lodge offers a seasonal menu that showcases fresh, locally sourced ingredients, making it a favorite for both casual diners and those seeking a memorable evening out. Indoor and outdoor seating available with lunch, dinner, and brunch service.

      Well, it was time for a Girl's Night Out. We decided on Clyde's because it has something for everyone. Are you craving seafood? Clyde's has it. Are you craving beef? Clyde's has it. Do you have food allergies? Clyde's provides excellent care in preparing meals for people with food allergies.

      We love the decor and usually ask to sit in the front dining room. They have all kinds of pictures and artifacts having to do with horses. There are real saddles, polo sticks, uniforms, and other decor that celebrate horses. We were fascinated with the ambiance.

      For dinner, one guest got the crab cake platter. The crabcake was delicious. It was fresh, not any filler, and seasoned well. It was accompanied by crispy French fries and cool creamy coleslaw.

      Another guest, got the Biria tacos. She loved them and said they were flavorful and tasty. The dipping sauce was great. I would recommend getting a side dish with this entry.

      The third guest ordered the cheeseburger and fries. She was delighted with her meal. It was a generous portion and she even ended up taking some home.

      Service was great and we were carefully attended to for drink refills or whatever we needed.

      For dessert, one guest got the raspberry sorbet and she really liked the taste.

      But, two of us shared the bread pudding with ice cream and that was a show stopper. It was soft, sweet, and caramelized. It was Amazing. I highly recommend you order it.

      All of this good food and good service isn't cheap, but exceptional and well worth it. I am sure the ladies and I will be back soon.

      Clyde's in Tower Oaks has always been one of our favorite places for birthdays, anniversaries, and brunches. But, I was surprised and happy to learn that they have a devoted gluten free and celiac free menu.

      My granddaughter, who has a gluten intolerance and celiacs disease taught me about their menu items. We really struggle to find a sit down restaurant that will adhere to her dietary restrictions.

      Clyde's has beautifully decorated dining areas that make dinner feel really special. My granddaughter ordered the Beria tacos and our waitress was amazing. We told her about our dietary restrictions and she said that she would check with the chef to make sure, there was nothing in our order that would upset my granddaughter's stomach.

      Key, heavens opening up and a huge rainbow appearing. We were so happy and my granddaughter demolished those tacos and fries. She loved them and ate every last bite.

      I ordered the crab cake sandwich with french fries. It was fresh and delicious. We had a real girls night out. We were so full, that there was no room for dessert.

      Beautiful surroundings, fabulous food, and great service. We will surely be back for another meal.

      Clyde's is one of the few places in the Gaithersburg/Rockville/North Bethesda area that's actually open late (1am Fri/Sat and midnight otherwise) and that serves actual food (i.e. not a dive bar or diner). Also - oysters are half price after 10pm! Can't believe it took me so long to realize this. It is the PERFECT place to come after a play or movie and get a bite to eat in a comfortable setting. The oysters we had were delicious. Both bars were also full and looked like a good scene if that's your thing - we sat in the dining area with the canoe.

      Dined here on Labor Day at midday off the brunch menu. Lots of great options (breakfast and otherwise) at a variety of price points. Sat outside on the porch and it was simply lovely - so refreshing to have actual cloth napkins and a cloth tablecloth when dining out. Blueberry scones were delicious - the plate came with two good-sized scones (with icing), butter, and lemon curd (yum!!) - scones were soft with lots of large blueberries inside. Had the fried zucchini sandwich which was big enough for two meals and packed with tasty fresh ingredients - the roll was soft and delicious. This is not a bargain restaurant but if you are looking for great service and an elevated comfortable atmosphere that can seat a crowd, this is your place. Great for a date, work dinner, or large family dinner where you are trying to accommodate a range of tastes. Also lots of great spots for group photos!

      This review is for brunch served on a Sunday. We had a table outside facing a pond. There are only 5 tables available and they are first come first serve. We got to the restaurant before it opened at 11 am.

      While waiting 10 minutes before the restaurant opened, there was a broken wine bottle on the sidewalk. I had to tell people to be careful. This should have been cleaned up by staff much earlier since this is a safety hazard if someone fell and got injured from the broken glass.

      Our waitress was friendly in the beginning, but then stopped because we didn't order any alcoholic drinks with our meals. We noticed a big difference in her customer service at the nearby tables. When she dropped the check off, it was in silence. No thank you, no smile, no eye contact. I have received much better service from staff at less upscale restaurants. Managers should train their staff to be pleasant to ALL customers, not just those who order liquor.

      Finally, the brunch entrees were disappointing. The traditional Eggs Benedict with poached eggs, Canadian bacon, muffins with potatoes were overcooked and dry. The Brioche French Toast was soggy.

      I used to look forward to coming here, but not anymore. I would not recommend having brunch. Better for you to go somewhere else and feel welcomed.

      We came for an early Valentine's Day dinner on Sunday, 2/6/22 to avoid massive crowds on the following weekend. We didn't have any reservations and were seated right away. There are various dining rooms available. The one near the front of the restaurant looked like the formal dining room. We were seated in the back dining room, which was more casual like a lodge.

      All the wait staff wore masks and were friendly and courteous. We tried the white wine sangria, but didn't know it would cost $15.99 until the bill came, and it had a lot of ice in the glass. They don't offer red sangria any more, which we tried in the past and cost less. For the appetizer, we had fried calamari for $15.99, and it was delicious and crispy. None of the calamari was tough or chewy.

      For entrees, we had the Icelandic Cod and Roasted Half Chicken Marsala. Each cost $19.99. They were large entrees, tasty, and flavorful. Nothing dry or overcooked. Both are highly recommended!

      We were too full to have dessert. Overall, a very pleasant experience. We enjoyed seeing the decor and lights throughout the restaurant. We will return again!
